WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.310 --> 00:00:04.310
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:00:04.310 --> 00:00:08.080
The man I'm here to
introduce and interview

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:10.600
really needs no
introduction as you can

00:00:10.600 --> 00:00:11.940
tell by how full the room is.

00:00:11.940 --> 00:00:13.850
But I'm going to
give him one anyway.

00:00:13.850 --> 00:00:15.530
According to Wikipedia--

00:00:15.530 --> 00:00:16.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:16.030 --> 00:00:18.540
--professor Richard
Dawkins is a pathologist,

00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:20.567
evolutionary
biologist, and writer.

00:00:20.567 --> 00:00:22.400
He's also made a bunch
of documentary films.

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:27.510
Unlike President Obama,
Professor Dawkins

00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:29.436
actually was born in Kenya.

00:00:29.436 --> 00:00:30.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:30.330 --> 00:00:33.170
His father was a civil servant
in the British Colonial Service

00:00:33.170 --> 00:00:35.540
in what is modern day Malawi.

00:00:35.540 --> 00:00:37.170
He studied zoology
at Oxford where,

00:00:37.170 --> 00:00:41.810
after a stint at UC Berkeley,
he returned to teach.

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:45.430
During this period, he wrote
his first popular book,

00:00:45.430 --> 00:00:47.950
"The Selfish Gene."

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:51.170
In this work, he argued strongly
that natural selection does not

00:00:51.170 --> 00:00:53.600
occur at the species
population or individual level,

00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:55.250
but rather at the
gene level itself.

00:00:55.250 --> 00:00:58.280
In 1995, after several more
successful publications,

00:00:58.280 --> 00:01:01.010
he was appointed to be
the Simonyi Professor

00:01:01.010 --> 00:01:03.030
for Public Understanding
of Science, which

00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:05.010
is a position created
by Charles Simonyi,

00:01:05.010 --> 00:01:08.307
the man behind Microsoft Office
and the Hungarian notation they

00:01:08.307 --> 00:01:09.015
use at Microsoft.

00:01:09.015 --> 00:01:11.515
So all you ex-Microsoft
folks that are here.

00:01:11.515 --> 00:01:13.890
And the position was created
with the express requirement

00:01:13.890 --> 00:01:16.500
that Professor Dawkins
be its first holder.

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:18.900
He wrote many popular
science books, including

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:21.720
"Climbing Mount Improbable"
and "The Ancestor's Tale,"

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:23.767
in which he took
complicated concepts,

00:01:23.767 --> 00:01:25.600
like the probabilities
involved in evolution

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:27.183
and the connection
of common ancestors

00:01:27.183 --> 00:01:29.040
with humans and other
species, and made

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:30.790
them understandable
to the average reader.

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:32.930
One might say that he
organized some information

00:01:32.930 --> 00:01:34.330
and made it more accessible.

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:37.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:39.670
RICHARD DAWKINS: That's
an in-group [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:39.670 --> 00:01:43.627
MALE SPEAKER: So our
mission here at Google

00:01:43.627 --> 00:01:45.210
is to organize the
world's information

00:01:45.210 --> 00:01:46.810
and make it more
accessible and usable.

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:47.430
RICHARD DAWKINS:
Well, my mission

00:01:47.430 --> 00:01:49.770
is to make morality
intelligently designed.

00:01:49.770 --> 00:01:51.496
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:52.735 --> 00:01:54.360
MALE SPEAKER: Professor
Dawkins started

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:56.080
to attract a lot more
widespread attention,

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:58.455
for better or for worse, with
the publication of "The God

00:01:58.455 --> 00:02:00.930
Delusion" in 2006,
which was sort

00:02:00.930 --> 00:02:05.436
of more of a full frontal
assault on religion.

00:02:05.436 --> 00:02:07.560
In it, he argues that God
almost certainly does not

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:09.949
exist and gives many
explanations for why

00:02:09.949 --> 00:02:12.830
he believes it's harmful
to hold such beliefs

00:02:12.830 --> 00:02:16.610
and why they're not necessary to
explain, for example, morality.

00:02:16.610 --> 00:02:20.095
He followed up this book with
"The Greatest Show on Earth,"

00:02:20.095 --> 00:02:22.800
in which he gathered together
a massive amount of evidence

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:24.390
for evolution,
again, making it very

00:02:24.390 --> 00:02:26.000
accessible to a lay reader.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.210
I actually really,
really love this book.

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:30.457
I found it truly inspiring.

00:02:30.457 --> 00:02:32.040
It really made it
clear to me just how

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:35.287
overwhelming the case is for
evolution by natural selection.

00:02:35.287 --> 00:02:37.120
I remember finishing
the book on an airplane

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:39.210
and sitting there just
for the rest of the flight

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:45.031
just sort of in awe of
just how strong the case is

00:02:45.031 --> 00:02:47.030
for evolution, how much
evidence we've gathered.

00:02:49.649 --> 00:02:51.940
In 2006, he also founded The
Richard Dawkins Foundation

00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:54.790
for Reason and Science, which
is a nonprofit organization

00:02:54.790 --> 00:02:56.560
dedicated to promoting
scientific literacy

00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:58.142
and secularism.

00:02:58.142 --> 00:02:59.600
Specifically, he
wants to encourage

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:02.551
us to use our critical thinking
skills in our day-to-day lives

00:03:02.551 --> 00:03:04.800
and allow secular views to
be more welcome in politics

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:06.977
and policy making.

00:03:06.977 --> 00:03:09.310
Professor Dawkins retired
from the Simonyi Professorship

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:11.410
in 2008, since which he's
written a book directed

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:13.740
at children, "The Magic of
Reality-- How We Know What's

00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:16.047
Really True," which,
I must add, is also

00:03:16.047 --> 00:03:17.088
delightfully illustrated.

00:03:20.757 --> 00:03:21.840
I've been saving this one.

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:23.620
I think it's about time I
let my daughter read it.

00:03:23.620 --> 00:03:26.290
She's got a bunch of questions
that are answered directly

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:27.660
in that book.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:30.860
So the book he's here to
promote is "Brief Candle

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:32.540
in the Dark-- My
Life in Science,"

00:03:32.540 --> 00:03:35.050
which is the second part
of a two-volume memoir.

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:37.080
The first book, "An
Appetite for Wonder,"

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:39.234
is about his childhood,
youth, and time up

00:03:39.234 --> 00:03:40.650
until he wrote
"The Selfish Gene."

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:43.076
So please join me in welcoming
Professor Richard Dawkins.

00:03:43.076 --> 00:03:46.482
[APPLAUSE]

