[LAUGHTER]

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:50.497
MALE SPEAKER: So the story about
how you met your wife actually

00:04:50.497 --> 00:04:52.830
kind of ties back to a bunch
of things that folks here--

00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:53.705
RICHARD DAWKINS: Yes.

00:04:53.705 --> 00:04:57.400
Perhaps I might read a
little passage on that.

00:04:57.400 --> 00:05:00.570
Do you have the page number?

00:05:00.570 --> 00:05:03.300
Here we are.

00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:06.520
"This was 1992
when Douglas Adams

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:08.440
reached his 40th birthday.

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:11.850
And his party was memorable
for a particular reason.

00:05:11.850 --> 00:05:15.240
It was there that he introduced
me to the actress, Lalla Ward,

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:17.540
whom he had known from
the days when "Doctor Who"

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:20.580
was at its wittiest because
he was the script editor.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.800
And she and Tom Baker gave
added value to the wit

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:27.390
by their inventively ironic
playing of the two leading

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:28.930
roles.

00:05:28.930 --> 00:05:33.600
At the birthday party, Lalla
was talking to Stephen Fry

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:36.340
when Douglas led me
over and introduced us.

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:39.410
Douglas and Stephen are
both absurdly much taller

00:05:39.410 --> 00:05:42.050
than Lalla and me,
so it was natural

00:05:42.050 --> 00:05:43.580
that we should find
ourselves facing

00:05:43.580 --> 00:05:47.580
each other under a Gothic arch
formed by Douglas and Stephen

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:52.040
as they exchanged lofty
witticisms high above us.

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.280
Through the archway,
I shyly offered

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:55.820
to refill Lalla's glass.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:58.680
And when I returned, we
rapidly reached agreement

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:01.990
that the party was too
noisy for conversation.

00:06:01.990 --> 00:06:05.470
'I suppose by any faint chance,
it wouldn't just possibly be

00:06:05.470 --> 00:06:08.830
a good idea to go out for a
quick meal and, of course,

00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:12.850
return later.' We discreetly
slipped away and found

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:16.470
an Afghan restaurant
off the Marylebone Road.

00:06:16.470 --> 00:06:18.380
That Lalla had read
"The Selfish Gene"

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:21.520
and watched my Christmas
Lectures was gratifying.

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:24.450
That she had read "The
Extended Phenotype" and Darwin,

00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:27.750
as well, was too
good to be borne.

00:06:27.750 --> 00:06:30.390
I subsequently discovered that,
in addition to Doctor Who's

00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:33.270
companion, she had played
a beautiful Ophelia

00:06:33.270 --> 00:06:37.030
to Derek Jacobi's "Hamlet"
in the BBC TV production

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:40.120
and was also a talented
and versatile artist,

00:06:40.120 --> 00:06:42.800
published author,
and book Illustrator.

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:45.730
As I said, too good to be borne.

00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:47.870
We didn't return to the party."

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:51.640
Miriam Rothschild is a very
distinguished biologist

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:55.840
and member of the immensely
wealthy Rothschild family.

00:06:55.840 --> 00:06:58.320
And she's a great character.

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:00.880
She lives in a house
deep in a wood, which

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:03.390
looks like a kind of fairy tale
house covered with creepers.

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:06.620
You need a machete to find it.

00:07:06.620 --> 00:07:12.630
And her garden consists
of wild weeds and grasses

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:14.720
breaking against
the house like waves

00:07:14.720 --> 00:07:17.700
and going into the
French windows like waves

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:20.280
coming inside the house.

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:23.010
She has an annual
dragonfly party,

00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:25.340
which is to celebrate
her conservation measures

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:28.770
of dragonflies around her lake.

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:32.276
It's a very large party with
about 80 people, I suppose.

00:07:32.276 --> 00:07:36.500
And one year, she said, come
and sit by me, dear boy.

00:07:36.500 --> 00:07:39.220
But, first, go and carve
me a slice of venison--

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:40.620
a very small slice, mind.

00:07:40.620 --> 00:07:41.620
I'm a strict vegetarian.

00:07:41.620 --> 00:07:43.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:45.380 --> 00:07:47.630
And the scarf story
was that she's

00:07:47.630 --> 00:07:49.960
the world authority on fleas.

00:07:49.960 --> 00:07:52.710
And so Lalla was trying to
raise money for a charity

00:07:52.710 --> 00:07:56.886
that she runs, which is
called Denville Hall.

00:07:56.886 --> 00:07:59.880
It's an old people's
home for old actors.

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:03.420
And so I encouraged her
to paint an enormous silk

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:09.370
scarf, a gigantic silk scarf,
because Miriam Rothschild wears

00:08:09.370 --> 00:08:11.140
silk scarves.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:13.880
And she painted nine
different species of flea,

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:19.080
hugely magnified images
of fleas on this scarf.

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:21.240
And I sent it off
with a covering note

00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:22.880
explaining about the charity.

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:27.190
And, eventually, Dame
Miriam wrote back and said,

00:08:27.190 --> 00:08:32.309
"I shall keep the handkerchief,
but tell your wife

00:08:32.309 --> 00:08:35.010
that she has sadly
underestimated

00:08:35.010 --> 00:08:36.530
the penis of the male flea."

00:08:36.530 --> 00:08:37.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:37.860 --> 00:08:40.510
"As you know, it is
proportionately the largest

00:08:40.510 --> 00:08:41.520
in the animal kingdom."

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.039
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:43.039 --> 00:08:46.630
And she wrote a generous
check to the charity,

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:52.010
and accompanied it with her
own book on flea micro-anatomy,

00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:55.100
inscribed to Lalla
with a note that said,

00:08:55.100 --> 00:08:58.864
"See page 272 for
vagina of mole flea."

00:08:58.864 --> 00:09:00.748
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:02.050 --> 00:09:03.800
MALE SPEAKER: So people
often perceive you

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:05.610
as being sort of
cold and calculated.

00:09:05.610 --> 00:09:09.742
But, in this book, there are
a lot of stories that you have

00:09:09.742 --> 00:09:14.250
that are very sentimental
and emotional.

00:09:14.250 --> 00:09:18.139
In particular,
one that struck me

00:09:18.139 --> 00:09:23.730
involved an experiment that
you were talking about,

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:25.820
having to do with
vision of the human eye.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:26.630
I was wondering if you
might tell us about that.

00:09:26.630 --> 00:09:28.740
RICHARD DAWKINS: I was
invited in the early 1990s

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:30.630
to give the Royal
Institution Christmas

00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:32.650
Lectures for children.

00:09:32.650 --> 00:09:36.230
This started out in
the 1820s, founded

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:38.350
by Michael Faraday, who
gave the lectures himself

00:09:38.350 --> 00:09:40.340
on many occasions.

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:42.730
They've now become
five one-hour lectures

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:44.970
around Christmas
time every year.

00:09:44.970 --> 00:09:48.120
And one scientist is
invited to give them.

00:09:48.120 --> 00:09:49.540
Nowadays, they're televised.

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:52.950
It's quite an
intimidating thing.

00:09:52.950 --> 00:09:55.170
The whole thing is very
highly choreographed.

00:09:55.170 --> 00:09:57.600
There's a tradition
starting with Faraday

00:09:57.600 --> 00:10:00.730
that you don't have
slides, or very few slides.

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:03.440
Instead, you call
the children out

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:07.224
to assist with demonstrations,
rather like conjurers do.

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:14.980
"In lecture five, I was talking
about a revealing difference

00:10:14.980 --> 00:10:18.810
between two ways in which
the retinal image can move."

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:23.990
If you shut one eye, and
poke-- you don't even

00:10:23.990 --> 00:10:25.000
need to shut the one.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.390
Poke the other eye
with your finger.

00:10:27.390 --> 00:10:30.470
You see the world move as
if there's an earthquake,

00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:33.480
not surprising because the
retinal image is moving.

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:37.750
But if you swivel your eyes
around in their sockets using

00:10:37.750 --> 00:10:41.550
the muscles that are
supposed for that purpose,

00:10:41.550 --> 00:10:43.330
then you don't
see an earthquake.

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:44.850
The world appears to be still.

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:46.840
You're just looking at
a different part of it,

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:53.170
even though the retinal image is
moving in the same kind of way.

00:10:53.170 --> 00:10:54.710
In one case, you
see an earthquake.

00:10:54.710 --> 00:10:56.970
In the other case, you don't.

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:59.930
Well, there's a theory
about why this happens

00:10:59.930 --> 00:11:02.550
due to some German
workers, which

00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:05.040
is that when you give the
order-- when your brain gives

00:11:05.040 --> 00:11:07.930
the order-- to the eye to
move around in the normal way,

00:11:07.930 --> 00:11:13.470
swiveling in the socket, the
brain sends a copy of the order

00:11:13.470 --> 00:11:16.390
to the perceiving
part of the brain

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:20.470
and tells the brain to
expect the world to move.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:22.750
And so, since there's
no discrepancy

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:25.890
between the expected movement
and the observed movement,

00:11:25.890 --> 00:11:28.330
the world appears to be still.

00:11:28.330 --> 00:11:30.840
On the other hand, when
you poke your eyeball,

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:32.320
the copy doesn't go.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:34.690
There's no copy that says,
expect the world to move.

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:38.860
So you do see it as if
there was an earthquake.

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:40.740
So that's the background.

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:43.470
"I pretended I was going
to demonstrate the effect

00:11:43.470 --> 00:11:45.290
with a key experiment.

00:11:45.290 --> 00:11:48.400
I would paralyze the
eyeball-moving muscles

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:50.020
with an injection.

00:11:50.020 --> 00:11:53.380
Then, when the brain sent an
order to move the eyeball,

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:57.100
the eyeball would stay still,
but the copy of the instruction

00:11:57.100 --> 00:11:58.730
would still be issued.

00:11:58.730 --> 00:12:01.430
So the person would see
an apparent earthquake,

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:03.140
even though the
eyeball hadn't moved

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:06.010
and nor had the world,
the apparent movement

00:12:06.010 --> 00:12:09.450
being the discrepancy between
the expected and actual

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:12.420
observed zero eye movement.

