This being the Christmas
Lectures, the next thing to do

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:17.280
was to call for a volunteer."

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:19.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:24.680
"I produced a huge veterinary
hypodermic syringe,

00:12:24.680 --> 00:12:28.010
fit to sedate a
rhinoceros and asked,

00:12:28.010 --> 00:12:32.080
'Who would like to take part
in the experiment?' Normally,

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:34.570
the children at the Royal
Institution Lectures fall over

00:12:34.570 --> 00:12:38.010
themselves in their eagerness
to assist in demonstrations.

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:40.970
Surely, nobody would
volunteer in this case.

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:42.580
And I was about to
reassure everyone

00:12:42.580 --> 00:12:46.950
that it was only a joke when
one little girl of seven,

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:48.940
probably the youngest
in the audience,

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:51.980
hesitantly raised her hand.

00:12:51.980 --> 00:12:55.540
It was my darling daughter,
Juliet, sitting shyly

00:12:55.540 --> 00:12:57.390
by her mother.

00:12:57.390 --> 00:12:59.410
I still choke up a
little at the memory

00:12:59.410 --> 00:13:03.640
of her uncomprehending
loyalty and courage

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:05.640
in the face of the
monstrous hypodermic

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:07.960
that I was brandishing.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:12.862
Is it irrelevant that she is
now a promising young doctor?"

00:13:12.862 --> 00:13:14.320
MALE SPEAKER: So
one of the reasons

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:15.903
that that touched
me so much is I have

00:13:15.903 --> 00:13:17.970
a 6 and 1/2 year old daughter.

00:13:17.970 --> 00:13:22.500
And a lot of questions
are coming up

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:25.940
in how I raise her
around this age.

00:13:25.940 --> 00:13:28.150
One of the things
that happened recently

00:13:28.150 --> 00:13:31.461
was we're planning a trip
to Vietnam and Cambodia.

00:13:31.461 --> 00:13:32.960
And one of the
things we want to see

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:34.820
is the Temple of Angkor Wat.

00:13:34.820 --> 00:13:37.100
And when we went to
talk to her about this,

00:13:37.100 --> 00:13:41.090
she didn't understand
what a temple was.

00:13:41.090 --> 00:13:45.190
And, suddenly, my wife and
I were sort of on the spot.

00:13:45.190 --> 00:13:49.310
How do we teach our
daughter about religion

00:13:49.310 --> 00:13:52.756
without actually
teaching her religion,

00:13:52.756 --> 00:13:55.121
because that seems important?

00:13:55.121 --> 00:13:57.288
And I was wondering if you
had any thoughts on that.

00:13:57.288 --> 00:13:59.412
RICHARD DAWKINS: It's a
very important distinction.

00:13:59.412 --> 00:14:01.800
You can't get away from
teaching a child about religion

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:05.140
because the child would be
illiterate in the world today.

00:14:05.140 --> 00:14:07.540
You couldn't understand
European history, for example,

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:10.630
unless you understand that many
of the wars in European history

00:14:10.630 --> 00:14:13.490
have been between
Protestants and Catholics.

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:15.260
You can't understand
contemporary history

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:17.290
unless you understand
about Islam,

00:14:17.290 --> 00:14:20.830
and Sunnis and Shias
and things like that.

00:14:20.830 --> 00:14:24.810
You can't really take your
allusions in English literature

00:14:24.810 --> 00:14:28.730
unless you know
biblical references.

00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:31.720
So you've got to teach
children about religion.

00:14:31.720 --> 00:14:35.020
But to indoctrinate a child
in a particular religion

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:38.720
and tell a child-- a
six-year-old child--

00:14:38.720 --> 00:14:41.890
tell a six-year-old child,
you belong to this religion.

00:14:41.890 --> 00:14:44.485
And, therefore, you believe in
this, this, and this and not

00:14:44.485 --> 00:14:45.750
that, that, and that.

00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:47.790
That's child abuse.

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:50.160
Tying a label around
a child's neck

00:14:50.160 --> 00:14:52.730
as belonging to the same
religion as its parents

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:53.700
is child abuse.

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:55.320
Yet, we all do it.

00:14:55.320 --> 00:14:58.330
We all quite happily--
we would never say,

00:14:58.330 --> 00:15:01.640
this is a logical
Positivist child,

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:03.780
or this is an
Existentialist child.

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:04.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:08.650
This is a Hayekian
Monetarist child.

00:15:08.650 --> 00:15:10.180
Nobody would dream
of saying that.

00:15:10.180 --> 00:15:12.885
And, yet, we're quite happy
to talk about a Catholic child

00:15:12.885 --> 00:15:14.960
or a Muslim child.

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:18.520
I read a story only a
week ago of a mother.

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:19.840
She had just given birth.

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:23.440
And the midwife held up
the baby to the mother

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:26.540
and said "What religion is he?"

00:15:26.540 --> 00:15:30.630
And the mother said, "Isn't he
a little bit too young to know?"

00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:32.314
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:36.286
MALE SPEAKER: So also,
reading through the book,

00:15:36.286 --> 00:15:37.702
I noticed a lot
of things actually

00:15:37.702 --> 00:15:40.800
that made me think about
what we do here at Google.

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:42.985
One of the things
that came to mind

00:15:42.985 --> 00:15:44.360
is the fact that,
here at Google,

00:15:44.360 --> 00:15:46.680
we're sort of working at
the forefront of machine

00:15:46.680 --> 00:15:49.000
translation.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.230
And you had several anecdotes in
your book about the experiences

00:15:54.230 --> 00:15:56.770
you've had trying to
translate your books and how--

00:15:56.770 --> 00:15:57.645
RICHARD DAWKINS: Yes.

00:15:57.645 --> 00:16:00.100
MALE SPEAKER: --that
worked or not worked.

00:16:00.100 --> 00:16:03.420
RICHARD DAWKINS: Well,
the first experience I had

00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:07.750
was the German translation
of "The Selfish Gene."

00:16:07.750 --> 00:16:10.610
I had a letter from
a woman in Germany

00:16:10.610 --> 00:16:13.040
who said that the
translation was

00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:16.780
so good that it was though
author and translator were

00:16:16.780 --> 00:16:18.537
twin souls.

00:16:18.537 --> 00:16:20.370
I thought that was
wonderful, so I looked up

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:24.535
the name of the German
translator, Karin de Souza

00:16:24.535 --> 00:16:27.214
Ferreira.

00:16:27.214 --> 00:16:28.630
Not exactly the
sort of name you'd

00:16:28.630 --> 00:16:31.750
expect of a German
translator, but never mind.

00:16:31.750 --> 00:16:33.130
I was immensely impressed.

00:16:33.130 --> 00:16:36.980
And I told the story to a German
Swiss colleague, Hans Kummer,

00:16:36.980 --> 00:16:39.870
a famous primatologist.

00:16:39.870 --> 00:16:44.220
And I'd only got as far
as saying twin souls.

00:16:44.220 --> 00:16:45.380
I didn't mention her name.

00:16:45.380 --> 00:16:46.910
I just got as far as twin souls.

00:16:46.910 --> 00:16:50.120
And he pointed his finger at
me and said Karin de Souza

00:16:50.120 --> 00:16:51.002
Ferreira?

00:16:51.002 --> 00:16:52.859
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:52.859 --> 00:16:55.150
I thought that was a pretty
good recommendation, a kind

00:16:55.150 --> 00:16:56.930
of independent recommendation.

00:16:56.930 --> 00:17:01.090
I haven't always been so lucky.

00:17:01.090 --> 00:17:07.170
When the Spanish translation
of "The God Delusion" came out,

00:17:07.170 --> 00:17:09.069
I received three
independent letters

00:17:09.069 --> 00:17:12.760
from Spanish-speaking people
who also spoke good English say,

00:17:12.760 --> 00:17:16.335
"It was so bad, it was probably
done by Google Translate."

00:17:16.335 --> 00:17:19.664
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:22.140 --> 00:17:26.770
In other words, literal
translations of idioms.

00:17:26.770 --> 00:17:32.140
But I must say that the Spanish
publishers manned up and agreed

00:17:32.140 --> 00:17:36.090
to destroy that edition,
and withdraw it,

00:17:36.090 --> 00:17:40.400
and commission an entirely new
translation, which I'm told

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:42.320
is very good.

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:45.226
So if you're interested
in the Spanish version,

00:17:45.226 --> 00:17:48.640
get the more recent one.

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:50.690
MALE SPEAKER: So
also of interest

00:17:50.690 --> 00:17:52.505
to some of the
folks here, I read

00:17:52.505 --> 00:17:57.730
that for "The Selfish Gene,"
you actually wrote your own word

00:17:57.730 --> 00:17:58.730
processor to write that?

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:01.105
RICHARD DAWKINS: Oh, that was
for "The Blind Watchmaker,"

00:18:01.105 --> 00:18:01.790
yes.

00:18:01.790 --> 00:18:04.000
I feel rather ashamed of
this because it really

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:07.560
is rediscovering the
wheel, not entirely.

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:11.330
I mean, I had an Apple
II computer at that time.

00:18:11.330 --> 00:18:15.600
And the standard word
processor supplied by Apple

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:17.580
was called Apple Writer.

00:18:17.580 --> 00:18:21.230
And there were no
lowercase letters.

00:18:21.230 --> 00:18:23.110
It was all uppercase letters.

00:18:23.110 --> 00:18:28.910
And uppercase was represented
by a reversal of color.

00:18:28.910 --> 00:18:30.969
And there was no
proper wrap-around.

00:18:30.969 --> 00:18:32.385
I mean, it was
really pretty poor.

00:18:34.890 --> 00:18:37.010
It didn't wrap around properly.

00:18:37.010 --> 00:18:39.710
So I did actually write
my own word processor,

00:18:39.710 --> 00:18:42.170
which was called Scrivener.

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:44.677
And it was an immense
labor, as you could imagine.

00:18:44.677 --> 00:18:46.260
I mean, you're all
professionals here.

00:18:46.260 --> 00:18:48.000
You can knock it
off in a weekend.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.950
But, for me, it took probably
the best part of a year,

00:18:52.950 --> 00:18:54.710
and then I wrote
one book with it.

00:18:54.710 --> 00:18:56.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:56.670 --> 00:18:58.200
And that was that.

00:18:58.200 --> 00:19:02.100
So I was addicted at that
time to computer programming.

00:19:02.100 --> 00:19:05.390
I expect many people here
understand about the addiction.

00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:08.830
And I would sort of
stay up all night,

00:19:08.830 --> 00:19:13.326
and not eat, and not sleep,
and things like that.

00:19:13.326 --> 00:19:15.450
MALE SPEAKER: It's not
uncommon amongst programmers

00:19:15.450 --> 00:19:18.230
to think that you're creating a
tool you're going to use over,

00:19:18.230 --> 00:19:20.355
and over, and over again
only to find that you only

00:19:20.355 --> 00:19:21.166
used it the once.

00:19:21.166 --> 00:19:22.492
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:22.492 --> 00:19:25.080
RICHARD DAWKINS: Douglas Adams
has a very good satire on that.

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:26.850
He was well aware
of the syndrome.

00:19:31.459 --> 00:19:33.500
MALE SPEAKER: So one of
the other things going on

00:19:33.500 --> 00:19:34.786
in the conversations
that we have at

00:19:34.786 --> 00:19:36.390
Google right now--
I know a lot of you

00:19:36.390 --> 00:19:38.320
are talking about interviewing.

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:41.970
And one of the things that we've
been talking about as regards

00:19:41.970 --> 00:19:45.629
interviewing is trying to
make the interview more blind.

00:19:45.629 --> 00:19:48.170
So when we write our interview
feedback, not including things

00:19:48.170 --> 00:19:53.470
like whether the candidate
was a woman or a man,

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:54.370
that sort of thing.

00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:56.082
And what made me
think of this was

00:19:56.082 --> 00:19:57.540
there's a passage
in the book where

00:19:57.540 --> 00:20:03.305
you talk about the importance
of double-blind experiments.

00:20:03.305 --> 00:20:04.180
RICHARD DAWKINS: Yes.

00:20:04.180 --> 00:20:08.410
MALE SPEAKER: And I
remember, as a grad student,

00:20:08.410 --> 00:20:12.540
preparing papers to be reviewed
in a double-blind format, which

00:20:12.540 --> 00:20:15.910
always just seems
like such a chore.

00:20:15.910 --> 00:20:19.320
But it turned out, it's actually
really, really important.

00:20:19.320 --> 00:20:23.899
And you touch on how important
double-blind evaluation is.

00:20:23.899 --> 00:20:26.440
RICHARD DAWKINS: It's immensely
important in medical research

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:29.070
where it's so easy to be fooled.

00:20:29.070 --> 00:20:33.700
And scientists now have to
be alive to the possibility

00:20:33.700 --> 00:20:37.440
that they are being fooled by
what they want to discover.

00:20:37.440 --> 00:20:39.050
They desperately
want to get a result.

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:40.690
And, with the best
will in the world,

00:20:40.690 --> 00:20:44.730
it's very hard not
to be influenced.

00:20:44.730 --> 00:20:48.270
So, I mean, I demonstrated
this in a television program

00:20:48.270 --> 00:20:51.290
where we were looking at
water divining, dowsing.

00:20:51.290 --> 00:20:53.630
And, since it was
television, we got

00:20:53.630 --> 00:20:57.000
a lot of volunteers, people who
were life-long practitioners

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:59.370
of dowsing, water divining.

00:20:59.370 --> 00:21:01.410
And they all were
absolutely confident

00:21:01.410 --> 00:21:04.110
that they could do
it, but they'd never

00:21:04.110 --> 00:21:08.110
been tested in double-blind
conditions before.

00:21:08.110 --> 00:21:11.540
So, first of all, we
had a tent, and there

00:21:11.540 --> 00:21:13.490
were lots of buckets of water.

00:21:13.490 --> 00:21:18.477
And they were walking
over the buckets of water.

00:21:18.477 --> 00:21:20.560
Or some of the buckets had
water, and some of them

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:22.030
didn't, of course.

00:21:22.030 --> 00:21:24.870
And when they could see
the water, their hazel

00:21:24.870 --> 00:21:28.245
twigs, or whatever it
was, dipped down exactly

00:21:28.245 --> 00:21:28.870
as they should.

00:21:28.870 --> 00:21:30.660
And it all went fine.

00:21:30.660 --> 00:21:32.840
And then we did it blind.

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:36.840
So there was no clue as
to where the water was.

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:38.927
Even the experimenter
didn't know

00:21:38.927 --> 00:21:41.010
where the water was because
he might inadvertently

00:21:41.010 --> 00:21:42.910
have given the game away.

00:21:42.910 --> 00:21:46.070
The person who had
laid out the buckets

00:21:46.070 --> 00:21:48.274
did so and then left
and went 100 yards away

00:21:48.274 --> 00:21:49.940
to the other side of
the tent so that he

00:21:49.940 --> 00:21:51.990
couldn't give any clues.

00:21:51.990 --> 00:21:54.490
And not a single one
of these dowsers--

00:21:54.490 --> 00:21:56.810
from all over the
country, not a single one

00:21:56.810 --> 00:21:59.090
scored above charts level.

00:21:59.090 --> 00:22:00.200
They were devastated.

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:03.420
One of the women actually
broke down in tears.

00:22:03.420 --> 00:22:07.509
She'd never been tested in
double-blind conditions before.

00:22:07.509 --> 00:22:09.050
There was another
story, which I tell

00:22:09.050 --> 00:22:12.900
in the book, of a
double-blind trial

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:19.180
of a diagnostic technique,
which is used by some quacks

00:22:19.180 --> 00:22:23.410
to test the efficacy of
some certain substances.

00:22:23.410 --> 00:22:26.760
I once actually did this myself.

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:29.025
I'd [INAUDIBLE] my neck,
and it was weekend,

00:22:29.025 --> 00:22:30.650
so I couldn't go to
my ordinary doctor.

00:22:30.650 --> 00:22:34.990
So I thought I'll go to an
alternative practitioner.

00:22:34.990 --> 00:22:38.200
And the first thing she did was
to do a diagnostic test, which

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:40.450
was to kind of arm wrestle me.

00:22:40.450 --> 00:22:41.450
I was lying on my back.

00:22:41.450 --> 00:22:45.260
And she was testing the
strength of my arm against hers,

00:22:45.260 --> 00:22:51.430
with and without a sealed
bottle of vitamin C on my chest.

00:22:51.430 --> 00:22:53.090
And she showed, to
her satisfaction,

00:22:53.090 --> 00:22:56.610
that when the sealed bottle
of vitamin C was on my chest,

00:22:56.610 --> 00:22:59.810
I was weaker-- sorry,
I was stronger.

00:22:59.810 --> 00:23:03.430
So when I sort of expressed
my skepticism, she said, yes!

00:23:03.430 --> 00:23:06.410
See, it's a marvelous
vitamin, isn't it?

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:07.880
But then I told a
story in the book

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:09.690
of another very
similar test using

00:23:09.690 --> 00:23:12.780
the same arm
wrestling technique,

00:23:12.780 --> 00:23:14.850
again, testing a substance.

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:17.130
This time, it was whether
fructose or glucose

00:23:17.130 --> 00:23:19.810
was put on your tongue,
whether it made you stronger.

00:23:19.810 --> 00:23:22.520
And in double-blind
conditions, there

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:23.770
was, of course, no difference.

00:23:23.770 --> 00:23:26.300
It didn't show any effect.

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:31.330
And the homeopath or whatever
he was who was doing the test

00:23:31.330 --> 00:23:33.380
said, "You see?

00:23:33.380 --> 00:23:36.190
This is why we don't
do double-blind trials.

00:23:36.190 --> 00:23:37.320
They never work!"

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:39.204
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:40.342 --> 00:23:42.050
MALE SPEAKER: I know
when I was preparing

00:23:42.050 --> 00:23:43.870
the introduction to
