00:24:20.214 --> 00:24:21.380
And so they were over there.

00:24:21.380 --> 00:24:22.088
And we were here.

00:24:22.088 --> 00:24:22.730
I was here.

00:24:22.730 --> 00:24:23.880
Christopher was there.

00:24:23.880 --> 00:24:26.660
And the philosopher,
A.C. Grayling, was there.

00:24:26.660 --> 00:24:28.880
So we were very close together.

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:33.760
And, at one point, one of the
religious people, Rabbi Julia

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:37.240
Neuberger, said something
irritating or silly.

00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:43.860
And Christopher Hitchens
interrupted and said, "How dare

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:44.450
you?

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:47.620
How dare you?"

00:24:47.620 --> 00:24:49.830
Except that he didn't.

00:24:49.830 --> 00:24:52.010
It's a false memory.

00:24:52.010 --> 00:24:54.220
I remembered it
extremely clearly.

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:57.550
And I still remember
it extremely clearly.

00:24:57.550 --> 00:24:58.410
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:58.410 --> 00:25:03.400
I used it in a eulogy speech
that I gave after his death

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:04.650
in Melbourne.

00:25:04.650 --> 00:25:06.580
I told the story.

00:25:06.580 --> 00:25:10.440
And only quite recently
when checking up

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:12.960
to write the story
down in this book,

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:17.380
I looked at the YouTube
video of the event.

00:25:17.380 --> 00:25:19.700
And it didn't happen.

00:25:19.700 --> 00:25:22.630
What did happen was that Rabbi
Neuberger was interrupted.

00:25:22.630 --> 00:25:26.360
She said something which he
did interrupt but much more

00:25:26.360 --> 00:25:26.997
quietly.

00:25:26.997 --> 00:25:28.330
And he didn't say, how dare you.

00:25:28.330 --> 00:25:32.940
He said something
much more gentle.

00:25:32.940 --> 00:25:37.120
He did say "how dare you"
about half an hour later

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:40.670
to a member of the audience
who asked a silly question.

00:25:40.670 --> 00:25:46.800
And he said that, although
he didn't believe in God,

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:48.600
he thought of himself
as a Christian

00:25:48.600 --> 00:25:50.650
because he was a moral person.

00:25:50.650 --> 00:25:52.131
Christopher said,
"How dare you!"

00:25:52.131 --> 00:25:54.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:54.540 --> 00:25:57.330
Well, that's bad enough
that I had a false memory.

00:25:57.330 --> 00:25:59.930
Then I was telling the
story of my false memory

00:25:59.930 --> 00:26:02.577
to Anthony Grayling,
the philosopher,

00:26:02.577 --> 00:26:04.910
because I thought he would
be interested in false memory

00:26:04.910 --> 00:26:06.770
syndrome, which, indeed, he was.

00:26:06.770 --> 00:26:09.970
But when I told him the
story, his jaw dropped.

00:26:09.970 --> 00:26:13.070
And he said, but I had
exactly the same false memory.

00:26:13.070 --> 00:26:15.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:15.600 --> 00:26:19.250
And it occurred to me
that in courts of law,

00:26:19.250 --> 00:26:24.180
for example, juries value
eyewitness testimony

00:26:24.180 --> 00:26:27.290
above all other
kinds of evidence.

00:26:27.290 --> 00:26:29.180
And imagine a lawyer
saying "I put it

00:26:29.180 --> 00:26:32.650
to you, ladies and gentlemen of
the jury, that two university

00:26:32.650 --> 00:26:36.650
professors both independently
had a false memory

00:26:36.650 --> 00:26:40.150
of an event which took place
not two yards from where

00:26:40.150 --> 00:26:41.690
they were sitting."

00:26:41.690 --> 00:26:44.400
But there's a sequel to
the story, which actually

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:46.570
came after the book was
published and, therefore, is

00:26:46.570 --> 00:26:48.300
not in the book.

00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:52.020
The sequel to the story is
that a young woman, I told her

00:26:52.020 --> 00:26:55.050
in a letter about what happened.

00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:59.050
And she said that she had the
same false memory from having

00:26:59.050 --> 00:27:00.460
watched the YouTube video.

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:02.730
So she had watched
the YouTube video,

00:27:02.730 --> 00:27:05.520
and she was the third
person who had attached this

00:27:05.520 --> 00:27:10.580
"how dare you" to the
response to Rabbi Neuberger,

00:27:10.580 --> 00:27:11.860
instead of to the right place.

00:27:11.860 --> 00:27:14.318
And I told her, well, go back
and look at the YouTube video

00:27:14.318 --> 00:27:15.450
again.

00:27:15.450 --> 00:27:19.440
She was actually
rather shattered by it.

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:21.649
Don't trust
eyewitness testimony.

00:27:21.649 --> 00:27:23.690
And probably don't trust
my autobiography either,

00:27:23.690 --> 00:27:24.356
for that matter.

00:27:24.356 --> 00:27:26.876
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:28.650 --> 00:27:30.540
MALE SPEAKER: So
one of the things

00:27:30.540 --> 00:27:32.620
I wanted to talk about,
as regards "The Greatest

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:38.170
Show on Earth," in that
book, you compile experiment

00:27:38.170 --> 00:27:42.610
after experiment validating
the claims and hypotheses

00:27:42.610 --> 00:27:45.890
of evolutionary theory.

00:27:45.890 --> 00:27:48.630
One of them that really stood
out was the Lenski experiments

00:27:48.630 --> 00:27:52.030
where they actually chart
the evolution of-- I think

00:27:52.030 --> 00:27:52.780
it's a bacterium--

00:27:52.780 --> 00:27:53.740
RICHARD DAWKINS:
Bacterium, yeah.

00:27:53.740 --> 00:27:55.465
MALE SPEAKER: --over thousands
and thousands and thousands

00:27:55.465 --> 00:27:56.130
of generations.

00:27:56.130 --> 00:27:58.090
And they even stop
it at certain points,

00:27:58.090 --> 00:28:00.920
set it aside, and show that they
can reproduce over and over.

00:28:00.920 --> 00:28:04.310
And I remember thinking, wow,
this is such a slam dunk case.

00:28:04.310 --> 00:28:07.410
But how do you--
something like that

00:28:07.410 --> 00:28:10.800
is only convincing
to somebody who

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:12.980
has an understanding
of the fundamentals

00:28:12.980 --> 00:28:15.030
of evolutionary theory.

00:28:15.030 --> 00:28:18.520
When you're faced with somebody
making an argument like,

00:28:18.520 --> 00:28:23.120
if we evolved from monkeys,
why are there still monkeys?

00:28:23.120 --> 00:28:26.540
That belies a complete
lack of understanding

00:28:26.540 --> 00:28:28.680
of even the fundamental--
the sort of stuff

00:28:28.680 --> 00:28:32.365
that should be taught in
middle school, for instance.

00:28:32.365 --> 00:28:33.990
RICHARD DAWKINS:
Well, it's just logic.

00:28:33.990 --> 00:28:37.000
You don't need to
be taught that.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.110
If Americans come
from Europeans,

00:28:39.110 --> 00:28:40.370
why are there still Europeans?

00:28:40.370 --> 00:28:42.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:42.890 --> 00:28:46.180
Somebody said at
lunch, just before.

00:28:46.180 --> 00:28:49.790
Yes, I mean, it's a
totally illogical--

00:28:49.790 --> 00:28:53.260
what it stems from is the idea
that evolution is a ladder.

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:55.020
And we're at the
top of the ladder,

00:28:55.020 --> 00:28:57.400
and then other apes
are just below us,

00:28:57.400 --> 00:28:59.680
and then monkeys are
below that, and so on.

00:28:59.680 --> 00:29:02.470
And so it's as though each
time a rung is climbed

00:29:02.470 --> 00:29:05.639
of the ladder, the
one below is kicked

00:29:05.639 --> 00:29:06.930
away or something of that sort.

00:29:06.930 --> 00:29:08.040
There is no ladder.

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:09.780
It's a branching tree.

00:29:09.780 --> 00:29:12.280
Every living creature,
every species

00:29:12.280 --> 00:29:16.785
is the tip of a twig of its
own evolutionary history.

00:29:16.785 --> 00:29:17.660
So there's no ladder.

00:29:17.660 --> 00:29:20.860
There's no sense in which we
superseded monkeys or anything

00:29:20.860 --> 00:29:21.670
like that.

00:29:21.670 --> 00:29:26.420
Monkeys and we both superseded
the common ancestor,

00:29:26.420 --> 00:29:30.462
which we share, some
20 million years ago.

00:29:30.462 --> 00:29:31.494
It's as simple as that.

00:29:31.494 --> 00:29:32.910
MALE SPEAKER: One
of the questions

00:29:32.910 --> 00:29:35.870
that my daughter asked me, I
want to say a few months ago,

00:29:35.870 --> 00:29:37.746
was, who was the first person?

00:29:37.746 --> 00:29:39.870
And that's actually the
title of the second chapter

00:29:39.870 --> 00:29:42.570
of your book, "The
Magic of Reality."

00:29:42.570 --> 00:29:45.210
And I remember really
struggling to explain

00:29:45.210 --> 00:29:50.099
to her the concept that there
really is no first person.

00:29:50.099 --> 00:29:52.390
And I was explaining this to
a friend of mine and said,

00:29:52.390 --> 00:29:55.230
well, my mom once dragged
me into a paint store

00:29:55.230 --> 00:29:58.360
and showed me the samples
of paint where, on one end,

00:29:58.360 --> 00:29:59.570
it was clearly yellow.

00:29:59.570 --> 00:30:01.403
And, on the other end,
it was clearly green.

00:30:01.403 --> 00:30:03.870
And then asked me, which
is first green sample?

00:30:03.870 --> 00:30:06.575
But I wouldn't have
thought of that

00:30:06.575 --> 00:30:08.740
to explain that to a child.

00:30:08.740 --> 00:30:09.804
So how do you--

00:30:09.804 --> 00:30:11.220
RICHARD DAWKINS:
Well, it's right.

00:30:11.220 --> 00:30:13.510
I mean, there never
was a first person.

00:30:13.510 --> 00:30:18.070
Every creature ever born
belonged to the same species

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:21.140
as its parents and its children.

00:30:21.140 --> 00:30:27.190
So it's just that if you
put enough generations end

00:30:27.190 --> 00:30:30.300
to end, if you start with
us today, and you go back,

00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:32.320
and back, and back,
and back, and back--

00:30:32.320 --> 00:30:38.820
if you go back 300 million
years, then you come to a fish.

00:30:38.820 --> 00:30:40.420
But there never
was a transition.

00:30:40.420 --> 00:30:43.610
There never was a sudden
transition from any one species

00:30:43.610 --> 00:30:44.840
to any other.

00:30:44.840 --> 00:30:46.940
The paint example is
a perfectly good one.

00:30:46.940 --> 00:30:49.540
Another one that I use
in "The Magic of Reality"

00:30:49.540 --> 00:30:51.600
is when we grow up,
we start as babies.

00:30:51.600 --> 00:30:52.630
And we become toddlers.

00:30:52.630 --> 00:30:53.610
And we become children.

00:30:53.610 --> 00:30:56.110
And we become teenagers,
and then young adults,

00:30:56.110 --> 00:30:59.674
and middle-aged, and then gaga.

00:30:59.674 --> 00:31:00.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:00.880 --> 00:31:03.480
But there never is
a sudden transition.

00:31:03.480 --> 00:31:05.360
You don't go to bed
one night middle-aged

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:07.200
and then wake up next
morning and say, oh, I

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.630
seem to be old now.

00:31:09.630 --> 00:31:11.470
It's a gradual, gradual change.

00:31:11.470 --> 00:31:14.380
And exactly the same
is true of evolution.

00:31:14.380 --> 00:31:16.170
It's a matter of
convenience that we

00:31:16.170 --> 00:31:19.690
are capable of
separating or saying,

00:31:19.690 --> 00:31:23.900
this definitely isn't a fish,
and this definitely is a fish.

00:31:23.900 --> 00:31:28.920
All the intermediates
are not present.

00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:32.180
But it's a category
mistake to say

00:31:32.180 --> 00:31:36.820
that because we distinguish
humans from, say, monkeys,

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:39.000
there must have
been a first human.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:40.720
There never was a first human.

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:44.580
It's just a gradual, gradual
transition everywhere you look.

00:31:44.580 --> 00:31:46.830
MALE SPEAKER: So I'm going
to change tack a little bit

00:31:46.830 --> 00:31:49.580
and talk more about
your experience

00:31:49.580 --> 00:31:54.140
as a scientist, as a
teacher, and the experiences

00:31:54.140 --> 00:31:55.130
that you had.

00:31:55.130 --> 00:31:58.430
For example, in the book, you
talk a lot about your life

00:31:58.430 --> 00:31:59.150
at Oxford.

00:31:59.150 --> 00:32:01.747
And, as an American
who's not familiar

00:32:01.747 --> 00:32:03.580
with that institition--
I mean, for example,

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:05.780
I was looking at the
history of the New College.

00:32:05.780 --> 00:32:09.581
But by the New, they meant
1379 or something like that.

00:32:09.581 --> 00:32:11.330
RICHARD DAWKINS: Well,
it was new in 1379.

00:32:11.330 --> 00:32:12.121
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:32:12.121 --> 00:32:12.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:12.930 --> 00:32:15.072
So there are a lot of
traditions, and formalities,

00:32:15.072 --> 00:32:20.050
and so forth that took place
there that would seem foreign

00:32:20.050 --> 00:32:23.190
and, dare I say, bizarre.

00:32:23.190 --> 00:32:25.440
RICHARD DAWKINS: Well, it
seemed pretty bizarre to me,

00:32:25.440 --> 00:32:26.190
as well, actually.

00:32:26.190 --> 00:32:27.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:27.320 --> 00:32:28.240
MALE SPEAKER: And I
was just wondering

00:32:28.240 --> 00:32:29.940
sort of what sort of influence
did that have on you?

00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:32.280
You talk, for instance,
about the formal dessert

00:32:32.280 --> 00:32:35.630
that you had where everybody
sits in a specific place,

00:32:35.630 --> 00:32:37.110
and they pass
around [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:37.110 --> 00:32:37.480
RICHARD DAWKINS: Yeah.

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:39.247
Well, these are
rather quaint customs.

00:32:39.247 --> 00:32:41.830
I sometimes suspect they're not
as ancient as you might think.

00:32:41.830 --> 00:32:44.390
I mean, they might just go
back to the 19th century,

00:32:44.390 --> 00:32:45.610
for all I know.

00:32:45.610 --> 00:32:50.685
But each generation kind
of thinks they're ancient.

00:32:50.685 --> 00:32:51.310
What can I say?

00:32:51.310 --> 00:32:55.240
I mean, I had to preside over
this custom of formal dessert

00:32:55.240 --> 00:33:00.260
where you pass around port
and nuts and snuff and things.

00:33:00.260 --> 00:33:03.527
When I was Sub-Warden of New
College-- which everybody

00:33:03.527 --> 00:33:05.360
becomes Sub-Warden at
some point-- and there

00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:09.000
was a terrible evening
when I became aware

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:13.080
of some kind of
ominous rumbling.

00:33:13.080 --> 00:33:15.160
And it was a very
distinguished professor

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:17.820
of philosophy, Michael Dummett.

00:33:17.820 --> 00:33:22.430
And he was saying, "I've never
been so insulted in my life.

00:33:22.430 --> 00:33:24.680
You have the most
atrocious manners.

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:27.540
You must be an Etonian.

00:33:27.540 --> 00:33:30.110
Etonian means somebody who
comes from Eton College, which

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:34.450
is Britain's most prestigious
and most expensive

00:33:34.450 --> 00:33:35.280
private school.

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:36.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:40.910
And the target of his
ire was Robin Lane Fox

00:33:40.910 --> 00:33:44.650
who was a fellow
in ancient history.

00:33:44.650 --> 00:33:46.825
Robin was hopping with
anxiety and saying, "But what

00:33:46.825 --> 00:33:47.324
have I done?

00:33:47.324 --> 00:33:48.660
What have I done?"

00:33:48.660 --> 00:33:52.460
And I couldn't work
out what it was.

00:33:52.460 --> 00:33:54.880
But I saw to it
in my hostly role

00:33:54.880 --> 00:33:59.520
that they were seated as far as
possible away from each other.

00:33:59.520 --> 00:34:02.240
And then, the next
day, I discovered

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:03.180
what the trouble was.

00:34:03.180 --> 00:34:06.570
It had boiled up from
lunchtime the previous day.

00:34:06.570 --> 00:34:08.889
And there was some trivial
little minor dispute

00:34:08.889 --> 00:34:11.310
over who should sit where
or something like that.

00:34:11.310 --> 00:34:13.989
And Professor Dummett
had harbored this rancor

00:34:13.989 --> 00:34:15.280
throughout the rest of the day.

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:18.480
And it had bubbled up to the
surface until, by the evening,

00:34:18.480 --> 00:34:21.000
it boiled over at dessert.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.469
But then, three days
later, he approached

00:34:23.469 --> 00:34:26.255
Robin Lane Fox and
most graciously

00:34:26.255 --> 00:34:28.380
apologized and said there
was nobody in the college

00:34:28.380 --> 00:34:30.190
that he would less
wish to insult.

00:34:30.190 --> 00:34:31.599
So it all ended up all right.

00:34:31.599 --> 00:34:32.859
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:32.859 --> 00:34:35.137
MALE SPEAKER: And while
you were at Oxford,

00:34:35.137 --> 00:34:37.261
there was a period of time
when your uncle was also

00:34:37.261 --> 00:34:38.635
a fellow at Oxford.

00:34:38.635 --> 00:34:40.760
RICHARD DAWKINS: Yes, my
father's youngest brother,

00:34:40.760 --> 00:34:43.020
my Uncle Collier.

00:34:43.020 --> 00:34:46.710
He was a wonderful character.

00:34:46.710 --> 00:34:51.010
One nice story about him was
that he came back from London

00:34:51.010 --> 00:34:54.020
on the last train to Oxford.

00:34:54.020 --> 00:34:57.860
And the car park at
the railway station

00:34:57.860 --> 00:35:02.210
had an arm that you had to put
a coin in the slot in order

00:35:02.210 --> 00:35:03.970
to release your car.

00:35:03.970 --> 00:35:07.510
And, at midnight,
the arm had broken.

00:35:07.510 --> 00:35:09.710
And so the entire
car park was trapped.

00:35:09.710 --> 00:35:11.950
Nobody could get out.

00:35:11.950 --> 00:35:15.030
My Uncle Collier
was on his bike,

00:35:15.030 --> 00:35:16.750
so it wasn't a problem to him.

00:35:16.750 --> 00:35:22.440
But showing supreme
altruism, he broke the arm,

00:35:22.440 --> 00:35:25.170
and marched up to the
station master's office,

00:35:25.170 --> 00:35:27.130
plunked it outside the
station master's office

00:35:27.130 --> 00:35:30.020
with a note giving
his name and address

00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:32.340
and saying exactly
why he'd done it.

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:38.390
And he was prosecuted and fined
for this public-spirited act.

00:35:38.390 --> 00:35:40.420
And then, many years
later after his death,

00:35:40.420 --> 00:35:44.770
actually, I happened to be going
to visit a rather old professor

00:35:44.770 --> 00:35:47.400
of physics, Nicholas Kurti.

00:35:47.400 --> 00:35:50.222
And when he heard my
name, he said, "Dawkins?

00:35:50.222 --> 00:35:51.680
Are you any relation
of the man who

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:53.140
broke the arm at the station?"

00:35:53.140 --> 00:35:54.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:54.300 --> 00:35:55.570
So I said, "Well, yes.

00:35:55.570 --> 00:35:56.540
I'm his nephew.

00:35:56.540 --> 00:35:57.440
And he said, "Come.

00:35:57.440 --> 00:35:58.960
Let me shake your hand.

00:35:58.960 --> 00:36:00.380
Your uncle was a hero."

00:36:00.380 --> 00:36:02.867
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:02.867 --> 00:36:04.700
I think the other story
you were thinking of

00:36:04.700 --> 00:36:08.610
is he was an expert
in statistics.

00:36:08.610 --> 00:36:11.620
He taught statistics
as well as forestry.

00:36:11.620 --> 00:36:16.990
So I used to take my own pupils
and ask him to tutor them

00:36:16.990 --> 00:36:17.669
in statistics.

00:36:17.669 --> 00:36:18.460
I didn't take them.

00:36:18.460 --> 00:36:20.826
I mean, I went and saw
him to ask if we would

00:36:20.826 --> 00:36:22.520
tutor my pupils in statistics.

00:36:22.520 --> 00:36:25.420
And I was doing that
one time in his office.

00:36:25.420 --> 00:36:27.120
And I was describing
this young man.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:29.842
I was saying things like, well,
he's a bit lazy, but he's OK.

00:36:29.842 --> 00:36:32.460
And you'll have to look after
him, make sure he works,

00:36:32.460 --> 00:36:33.160
and so on.

00:36:33.160 --> 00:36:36.040
And I noticed that my
uncle was taking notes.

00:36:36.040 --> 00:36:38.470
He wasn't taking
notes in English.

00:36:38.470 --> 00:36:42.040
This was the Department of
Forestry, the Imperial Forestry

00:36:42.040 --> 00:36:44.910
Institute at Oxford, which is
filled with old colonial types

00:36:44.910 --> 00:36:46.740
from all over Africa.

00:36:46.740 --> 00:36:50.621
And so I said, well, that's
very confidential of you,

00:36:50.621 --> 00:36:51.620
taking notes in Swahili.

00:36:51.620 --> 00:36:53.260
And he said, "Swahili?

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:54.360
Good god, no.

00:36:54.360 --> 00:36:56.740
Everyone in this
department speaks Swahili.

00:36:56.740 --> 00:36:57.870
This is Acholi."

00:36:57.870 --> 00:37:00.762
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:02.517 --> 00:37:04.850
MALE SPEAKER: One of my other
favorite parts in the book

00:37:04.850 --> 00:37:06.330
are, basically,
the parts where you

00:37:06.330 --> 00:37:08.621
talk about all the other
books that you've worked with.

00:37:08.621 --> 00:37:13.520
There are a lot of pictures
of colleagues and so forth.

00:37:13.520 --> 00:37:18.240
You talk about the debates and
the preferred mutual tutorials

00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:20.920
that you've done
with other folks.

00:37:20.920 --> 00:37:22.420
Who would you say
that you've worked

00:37:22.420 --> 00:37:24.690
with in that capacity that's
really had the biggest

00:37:24.690 --> 00:37:26.127
influence on you?

00:37:26.127 --> 00:37:28.460
RICHARD DAWKINS: I like the
idea of the mutual tutorial.

00:37:28.460 --> 00:37:31.530
I find that the
debate format is not

00:37:31.530 --> 00:37:33.980
an attractive one,
the format where

00:37:33.980 --> 00:37:36.180
you have 10 minutes
for the proposition,

00:37:36.180 --> 00:37:39.140
10 minutes for the opposition,
three minutes for rebuttal,

00:37:39.140 --> 00:37:41.057
three minutes for
rebuttal, and then a vote.

00:37:41.057 --> 00:37:43.140
I don't think that's the
way you get at the truth.

00:37:43.140 --> 00:37:46.730
I like the mutual tutorial
where you have a conversation.

00:37:46.730 --> 00:37:48.620
And it doesn't have
to be adversarial.

00:37:48.620 --> 00:37:51.990
Sometimes a conversation can
be between people who pretty

00:37:51.990 --> 00:37:55.030
much agree with each other.

00:37:55.030 --> 00:38:00.400
I suppose the best one
for me was Steven Pinker,

00:38:00.400 --> 00:38:03.150
the psychologist and linguist.

00:38:03.150 --> 00:38:05.320
And perhaps it was
the one that gave me

00:38:05.320 --> 00:38:08.540
the idea for the
mutual tutorial.

00:38:08.540 --> 00:38:12.920
We had an on-stage conversation
in a London theater,

00:38:12.920 --> 00:38:14.390
about 2,000 people.

00:38:14.390 --> 00:38:16.900
It was a very large audience.

00:38:16.900 --> 00:38:18.020
And it went very well.

00:38:18.020 --> 00:38:19.720
And we learned a
lot from each other.

00:38:19.720 --> 00:38:22.990
You sort of raise each other's
game in a funny kind of way.

00:38:22.990 --> 00:38:25.620
And precisely because
you're not disagreeing,

00:38:25.620 --> 00:38:27.680
you're actually learning
from each other.

00:38:27.680 --> 00:38:29.990
The BBC got to hear
of this, and they

00:38:29.990 --> 00:38:32.420
thought it might be
fun to reprise it

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:34.159
on television that evening.

00:38:34.159 --> 00:38:35.700
So they asked us
would we agree to go

00:38:35.700 --> 00:38:39.390
and have a shortened version of
our conversation on television.

00:38:39.390 --> 00:38:41.000
We said yes.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:44.170
And then the woman
producing it phoned me

00:38:44.170 --> 00:38:46.450
up to plan the program.

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:47.560
And she said, "Tell me.

00:38:47.560 --> 00:38:50.880
What's the nature of your
disagreement with Dr. Pinker?"

00:38:50.880 --> 00:38:53.180
And I said, "Well, I
don't think we really

00:38:53.180 --> 00:38:54.690
got much of a disagreement.

00:38:54.690 --> 00:38:56.190
We seem to agree
about most things."

00:38:56.190 --> 00:38:59.550
And she said, "No disagreement?

00:38:59.550 --> 00:39:01.310
No disagreement?"

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:03.954
She promptly cancelled
the whole thing.

00:39:03.954 --> 00:39:04.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:05.410 --> 00:39:06.410
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:08.400
So as we're getting toward
the end of our time,

00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:09.983
I wanted to take a
couple of questions

00:39:09.983 --> 00:39:14.880
off of our submitted
questions list.

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:16.824
The top one we have
right now says,

00:39:16.824 --> 00:39:18.490
"You must have rebutted
them all by now,

00:39:18.490 --> 00:39:20.490
so I'd be curious to know
what, in your opinion,

00:39:20.490 --> 00:39:22.720
are the best arguments out
there against evolution

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:24.690
and the nonexistence of deities?

00:39:24.690 --> 00:39:26.820
Which do you find the
hardest to rebut?"

00:39:26.820 --> 00:39:28.340
RICHARD DAWKINS: Those are
two quite different questions,

00:39:28.340 --> 00:39:28.840
by the way.

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:36.150
There is no decent
rebuttal of evolution.

00:39:36.150 --> 00:39:38.010
And there is no decent
argument in favor

00:39:38.010 --> 00:39:40.150
of the existence of deities.

00:39:40.150 --> 00:39:44.090
So if I attempt to answer that
question, I'm not in any sense

00:39:44.090 --> 00:39:46.660
admitting that there is a
good argument because I once

00:39:46.660 --> 00:39:51.720
made the mistake of saying the
best argument I could think

00:39:51.720 --> 00:39:59.740
of for the existence of a God
would be a deistic God who

00:39:59.740 --> 00:40:02.710
had something to do with the
fine-tuning of the universe.

00:40:02.710 --> 00:40:05.410
I think that is probably
the best argument around.

00:40:05.410 --> 00:40:08.424
It's still a very,
very bad argument,

00:40:08.424 --> 00:40:09.590
but it's the best one going.

00:40:09.590 --> 00:40:15.170
But when I said that once in
a debate actually with a man

00:40:15.170 --> 00:40:18.560
called John Lennox, two days
later he was up in Scotland

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:20.025
giving a lecture on his own.

00:40:20.025 --> 00:40:22.400
And he more or less announced
that I had become a deist--

00:40:22.400 --> 00:40:23.715
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:23.715 --> 00:40:26.090
--simply because I had said
out of all the bad arguments,

00:40:26.090 --> 00:40:27.664
this is the least bad.

00:40:27.664 --> 00:40:29.830
And I've since met this
problem over and over again.

00:40:29.830 --> 00:40:33.710
That if you say x is
bad, but y is worse,

00:40:33.710 --> 00:40:37.200
people will think you're
condoning x or somehow saying

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:39.380
that x is a good thing.

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:42.530
So I think the best argument
for the existence of a god

00:40:42.530 --> 00:40:44.452
is the fine-tuning argument.

00:40:44.452 --> 00:40:46.160
But it's still a very,
very poor argument

00:40:46.160 --> 00:40:48.640
because you still
have left unexplained

00:40:48.640 --> 00:40:51.860
where the fine tuner came from.

00:40:51.860 --> 00:40:55.860
The best argument
against evolution?

00:40:55.860 --> 00:40:56.535
There isn't one.

00:40:56.535 --> 00:41:01.940
I mean, there's just
no argument against it.

00:41:01.940 --> 00:41:04.231
I mean, there are reasons
why people don't get it,

00:41:04.231 --> 00:41:05.480
which is a different question.

00:41:05.480 --> 00:41:07.290
There are reasons why
people don't get it,

00:41:07.290 --> 00:41:13.860
such as that the time scale
involved is so huge that people

00:41:13.860 --> 00:41:19.470
find it difficult to
grasp how long a time has

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:22.500
been available for the
changes we're talking about.

00:41:22.500 --> 00:41:24.100
In a way, Darwin
had it right when

00:41:24.100 --> 00:41:27.120
he pointed to things
like dogs and pigeons

00:41:27.120 --> 00:41:29.160
where we know how
long it's taken.

00:41:29.160 --> 00:41:31.140
And actually,
Lenski's bacteria too,

00:41:31.140 --> 00:41:33.770
but Darwin didn't
know that, of course.

00:41:33.770 --> 00:41:37.372
It hasn't taken very long to
turn a wolf into a Pekingese.

00:41:37.372 --> 00:41:39.250
And when you think
that that's only

00:41:39.250 --> 00:41:41.430
taken a matter of
centuries, and then you

00:41:41.430 --> 00:41:45.240
think that to turn
a fish into a mammal

00:41:45.240 --> 00:41:50.415
has taken not just centuries but
hundreds of millions of years.

00:41:50.415 --> 00:41:52.980
And if you extrapolate
the amount of change

00:41:52.980 --> 00:41:55.470
from wolf to Pekingese
and multiply it

00:41:55.470 --> 00:42:00.180
by the number of centuries there
have been in 300 million years,

00:42:00.180 --> 00:42:04.600
you get an idea of how you
will not grasp evolution

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:09.550
unless you can somehow get your
mind around these immensities

00:42:09.550 --> 00:42:11.072
of time.

00:42:11.072 --> 00:42:13.280
MALE SPEAKER: It seems like
sort of the same problems

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:16.550
that we face, which is
obviously not as big of a deal,

00:42:16.550 --> 00:42:18.375
in terms of our
society and so forth,

00:42:18.375 --> 00:42:19.385
of getting people
to understand things

00:42:19.385 --> 00:42:21.456
like quantum mechanics
and general relativity

00:42:21.456 --> 00:42:25.138
that our brains are
designed to-- are designed?

00:42:25.138 --> 00:42:26.124
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:26.932 --> 00:42:28.890
--where everything is
middle of the road, and--

00:42:28.890 --> 00:42:31.098
RICHARD DAWKINS: I think
the word "designed" is fine.

00:42:31.098 --> 00:42:34.210
It's just that it's not
designed by an intelligence.

00:42:34.210 --> 00:42:35.790
I mean, I think the
remarkable thing

00:42:35.790 --> 00:42:39.310
is that brains which were
designed by natural selection

00:42:39.310 --> 00:42:45.050
to survive on the African
savannah as hunter gatherers,

00:42:45.050 --> 00:42:47.170
and to get a mate,
and rear a child,

00:42:47.170 --> 00:42:51.590
and avoid being eaten by
lions, fairly simple problems

00:42:51.590 --> 00:42:53.750
compared to quantum
theory or relativity.

00:42:53.750 --> 00:42:57.820
And yet, those very same brains
have the emergent property

00:42:57.820 --> 00:43:00.570
that they can understand
quantum theory.

00:43:00.570 --> 00:43:02.270
I can't, but some people can.

00:43:02.270 --> 00:43:03.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:03.540 --> 00:43:06.890
And it makes me proud to be
a member of the species homo

00:43:06.890 --> 00:43:09.184
sapiens.

00:43:09.184 --> 00:43:11.380
MALE SPEAKER: I'll take
one more off of our list

00:43:11.380 --> 00:43:15.250
here, which is, where do you
see the world 10 years from now,

00:43:15.250 --> 00:43:18.315
in terms of belief in myths
versus belief in science?

00:43:18.315 --> 00:43:20.690
It seems that the overall
trends are positive for science

00:43:20.690 --> 00:43:21.990
and negative for myth worldwide.

00:43:21.990 --> 00:43:24.281
There is also what seems to
be a backlash, for example,

00:43:24.281 --> 00:43:27.600
the rise of radical Islam
and the anthropogenic global

00:43:27.600 --> 00:43:29.120
warming denial by
many in the US.

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:29.995
RICHARD DAWKINS: Yes.

00:43:29.995 --> 00:43:32.940
I mean, I think if you look
on the broad sweep of history,

00:43:32.940 --> 00:43:35.970
things are going in
the right direction.

00:43:35.970 --> 00:43:40.060
If you take poll data in America
and in western and northern

00:43:40.060 --> 00:43:44.032
Europe, things are going
in the right direction.

00:43:44.032 --> 00:43:45.490
In Britain, for
example, the number

00:43:45.490 --> 00:43:51.510
of people who ticked the
Christian box in the 2001

00:43:51.510 --> 00:43:55.430
census was, I think, 73%.

00:43:55.430 --> 00:43:59.890
And, in the 2011
census, it was 54%.

00:43:59.890 --> 00:44:05.400
And my British foundation,
The Richard Dawkins Foundation

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:07.150
for Reason and Science,
which, by the way,

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:10.500
is much more
flourishing in America

00:44:10.500 --> 00:44:13.250
and is doing more sorts of
active things in America--

00:44:13.250 --> 00:44:16.550
please join The Richard
Dawkins Foundation for Reason

00:44:16.550 --> 00:44:17.850
and Science in America.

00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:25.570
But the British foundation did
a further survey of the people

00:44:25.570 --> 00:44:28.160
who ticked the Christian
box in the 2011 census

00:44:28.160 --> 00:44:32.230
and found that actually,
although it's still 54% ticked

00:44:32.230 --> 00:44:34.760
the Christian box, who actually
asked them supplementary

00:44:34.760 --> 00:44:37.910
questions, like, "Is Jesus
your Lord and Savior?"

00:44:37.910 --> 00:44:42.690
and, "Can you pick out
of this list of four,

00:44:42.690 --> 00:44:45.780
what is the first book
of the "New Testament?"

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:48.230
The number dropped
dramatically below that 54%.

00:44:48.230 --> 00:44:51.180
I mean, scarcely any
of them could really

00:44:51.180 --> 00:44:53.070
claim to be proper Christians.

00:44:53.070 --> 00:45:02.840
In America, the number of people
who subscribe to any religion,

00:45:02.840 --> 00:45:04.240
20% don't.

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:06.960
There are 20% of the
American electorate now

00:45:06.960 --> 00:45:10.570
who don't subscribe to any
religion according to polls.

00:45:10.570 --> 00:45:12.410
And that's a very high figure.

00:45:12.410 --> 00:45:17.360
It compares favorably with
any particular religion.

00:45:17.360 --> 00:45:20.930
So I think things are moving
in the right direction

00:45:20.930 --> 00:45:24.030
but with dips.

00:45:24.030 --> 00:45:26.750
It's a sawtooth rather
than a gradual trend.

00:45:26.750 --> 00:45:30.140
And, as you say, the
rise of radical Islam

00:45:30.140 --> 00:45:32.340
is a negative trend,
which may take

00:45:32.340 --> 00:45:35.291
a bit longer to get rid of.

00:45:35.291 --> 00:45:36.290
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:45:36.290 --> 00:45:39.230
So, with that, let's
thank our speaker.

00:45:39.230 --> 00:45:41.730
He's going to be signing books.

00:45:41.730 --> 00:45:44.080
Just to remind you, we won't
be personalizing them just

00:45:44.080 --> 00:45:46.009
because we won't have time.

00:45:46.009 --> 00:45:48.260
But, yeah, let's
thank our speaker.

00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:51.310
[APPLAUSE]

